==Signs and symptoms==
People with avoidant personality disorder are preoccupied with their own shortcomings and form relationships with others only if they believe they will not be rejected. Loss and rejection are so painful that these individuals will choose to be lonely rather than risk trying to connect with others.
* Hypersensitivity to [[Social rejection|rejection]]/[[criticism]]
* Self-imposed [[social isolation]]
* Extreme [[shyness]] or [[social anxiety|anxiety]] in social situations, though the person feels a strong desire for close relationships<ref name=line>{{cite web | title =Avoidant personality disorder | publisher= Healthline Networks | work =Avoidant personality disorder | url=http://www.healthline.com/galecontent/avoidant-personality-disorder | year = 2003 | accessdate=2006-02-26 | author =Gary Gilles M.A., Paula Ford-Martin M.A.}}</ref>
* Avoids physical contact because it has been associated with an unpleasant or painful stimulus
* Feelings of inadequacy
* Severe low [[self-esteem]]
* [[Self-loathing]]
* [[Mistrust]] of others
* [[Personal boundaries|Emotional distancing]] related to intimacy
* Highly [[self-conscious]]
* [[Self-criticism|Self-critical]] about their problems relating to others
* Problems in occupational functioning
* Lonely [[self-perception]], although others may find the relationship with them meaningful
* Feeling [[Inferiority complex|inferior]] to others
* In some more extreme cases — [[agoraphobia]]
* Utilizes [[fantasy (psychology)|fantasy]] as a form of [[escapism]] and to interrupt painful thoughts<ref name=sperry /><ref>[http://www.healthyplace.com/personality-disorders/avoidant-personality-disorder/avoidant-personality-disorder/menu-id-62/  Avoidant Personality Disorder], Real Mental Health, Inc.</ref>

